- Ministry of Light Industry;
- Ministry of Public Education;
- Ministry of Justice;
- Ministry of Post and Telecommunications;
- Ministry of Social Security;
- Ministry of Health;
- Ministry of State Security;
- Ministry of Transports;

1952:78.contentEn:
The citizens of the Romanian People's Republic shall have the right to rest.
The right to rest shall be ensured by: the establishment of an 8-hour working day for workers and employees; the reduction of the working day to less than 8 hours for certain professions with difficult working conditions and for sections with particularly difficult working conditions;
the establishment of paid annual holidays for all workers and employees; making available to the working people rest homes, sanatoriums and cultural institutions.

1952:85.contentEn:
In accordance with the interests of those who work and in order to strengthen the regime of people's democracy, the citizens of the Romanian People's Republic are guaranteed by law:
- a) freedom of speech;
- b) freedom of the press;
- c) freedom of assembly and meetings;
- d) freedom of processions and street demonstrations.
These rights are ensured by placing at the disposal of the working masses and their organizations the printing houses, paper depots, public buildings, streets, means of communication and other material conditions necessary for the exercise of these rights.

1965:13.contentEn:
In the Socialist Republic of Romania, the entire state activity aims at the development of the order and the flourishing of the socialist nation, the continuous increase of the material and cultural welfare of the people, ensuring the freedom and dignity of man, the multilateral affirmation of the human personality.
For this, the Romanian socialist state:
Organizes, plans and manages the national economy;
Protects socialist property;
Guarantees the full exercise of citizens' rights, ensures socialist legality and defends the rule of law;
Develops education of all levels, ensures the conditions for the development of science, art and culture, carries out health protection;
Ensures the defense of the country and organizes its armed forces;
Organizes relations with other states.

1986:13.contentEn:
In the Socialist Republic of Romania, the entire state activity is aimed at developing the order and flourishing of the socialist nation, the continuous increase of the material and cultural well-being of the people, ensuring the freedom and dignity of man, the multilateral affirmation of the human personality.
For this, the Romanian socialist state:
Organizes, plans and manages the national economy;
Protects socialist property;
Guarantees the full exercise of the rights of citizens, ensures socialist legality and defends the rule of law;
Develops education of all levels, ensures the conditions for the development of science, art and culture, carries out health protection;
Ensures the defense of the country and organizes its armed forces;
Organizes relations with other states.

1986:43.contentEn:
The Grand National Assembly has the following main attributions:
1. Adopts and amends the Constitution of the Socialist Republic of Romania;
2. Regulates the electoral system;
3. Decides on consulting the people, by referendum, on measures of particular importance concerning the supreme interests of the country;
4. Adopts the single national plan for economic and social development, the state budget and the general account of the budget year's closure;
5. Organizes the Council of Ministers; establishes the general rules for the organization and functioning of ministries and other central state bodies;
6. Regulates the judicial organization and the Prosecutor's Office;
7. Establishes the rules for the organization and functioning of the people's councils;
8. Establishes the administrative organization of the territory;
9. Grants amnesty;
10. Ratifies and denounces international treaties that involve the amendment of laws;
11. Elects and recalls the President of the Socialist Republic of Romania;
12. Elects and recalls the State Council;
13. Elects and recalls the Council of Ministers;
14. Elects and recalls the Supreme Tribunal and the Prosecutor General;
15. Exercises general control over the application of the Constitution. Only the Grand National Assembly decides on the constitutionality of laws;
16. Controls the activity of the President of the Socialist Republic of Romania and of the State Council;
17. Controls the activity of the Council of Ministers, of the ministries and of the other central bodies of the state administration;
18. Listens to reports on the activity of the Supreme Tribunal and controls its guiding decisions;
19. Controls the activity of the Prosecutor's Office;
20. Exercises general control over the activity of the people's councils;
21. Establishes the general line of foreign policy;
22. Proclaims, in the interest of defending the country, public order or state security, a state of necessity, in some localities or throughout the entire territory of the country;
23. Declares partial or general mobilization;
24. Declares a state of war. A state of war may be declared only in the event of armed aggression against the Socialist Republic of Romania or against another state towards which the Socialist Republic of Romania has mutual defense obligations assumed through international treaties, if the situation for which the obligation to declare a state of war is established has occurred.

1986:63.contentEn:
The State Council permanently exercises the following main attributions:
1. Establishes the date of elections for the Grand National Assembly and the people's councils;
2. Establishes the manner of organizing and conducting the referendum;
3. Organizes the ministries and other central state bodies;
4. Ratifies and denounces international treaties, with the exception of those whose ratification is the competence of the Grand National Assembly;
5. Establishes military ranks;
6. Institutes decorations and honorary titles.

1986:64.contentEn:
In the interval between the sessions of the Grand National Assembly, the State Council exercises the following main attributions:
1. Establishes, without being able to amend the Constitution, norms with the power of law. The norms with the power of law are submitted, at the first session, to the debate of the Grand National Assembly, according to the procedure for adopting laws. The single national plan for economic and social development, the state budget, as well as the general account of the closing of the budget year, may be adopted by the State Council only when the Grand National Assembly cannot meet due to exceptional circumstances;
2. Appoints and dismisses the Prime Minister;
3. Appoints and dismisses the Council of Ministers and the Supreme Tribunal, when the Grand National Assembly cannot meet due to exceptional circumstances;
4. Gives the generally binding interpretation to the laws in force;
5. Grants amnesty;
6. Controls the application of the laws and decisions of the Grand National Assembly, the activity of the Council of Ministers, of the ministries and of the other central bodies of the state administration, as well as the activity of the Prosecutor's Office; hears reports from the Supreme Tribunal and controls its guiding decisions; controls the decisions of the people's councils;
7. Declares, in case of emergency, partial or general mobilization;
8. Declares, in case of emergency, the state of war. The state of war may be declared only in the case of an armed aggression against the Socialist Republic of Romania or against another state towards which the Socialist Republic of Romania has mutual defense obligations assumed through international treaties, if the situation for which the obligation to declare the state of war is established has occurred.
The attributions provided for in this Articolul may be exercised by the State Council also during the sessions of the Grand National Assembly, if the economic and social needs require the immediate adoption of measures, and the Grand National Assembly is not meeting in its plenum; the norms with the power of law adopted are submitted to the debate of the Grand National Assembly, according to the procedure for adopting laws, upon the resumption of work in the plenum.

1986:75.contentEn:
The President of the Socialist Republic of Romania shall, in accordance with the Constitution and the laws, perform the following main duties:
1. Presides over the State Council;
2. Presides over the meetings of the Council of Ministers when necessary;
3. Establishes the measures of particular importance concerning the supreme interests of the country, which are to be submitted by the Grand National Assembly for consultation with the people, by referendum;
4. Appoints and dismisses, upon the proposal of the Prime Minister, the Deputy Prime Ministers, Ministers and Presidents of other central bodies of the state administration, who are members of the Council of Ministers; appoints and dismisses the heads of the central state bodies, who are not members of the Council of Ministers; appoints and dismisses the members of the Supreme Tribunal;
5. During the time when the Grand National Assembly is not convened in its plenum, appoints and dismisses the President of the Supreme Tribunal and the Prosecutor General;
6. Grants the ranks of general, admiral and marshal;
7. Confers decorations and honorary titles; authorises the wearing of decorations conferred by other states;
8. Grants pardon;
9. Grants citizenship, approves renunciation of citizenship and withdraws Romanian citizenship; approves the establishment of domicile in Romania for citizens of other states;
10. Grants the right of asylum;
11. Establishes the ranks of diplomatic missions, accredits and recalls the diplomatic representatives of the Socialist Republic of Romania;
12. Receives the letters of accreditation and recall of the diplomatic representatives of other states;
13. Concludes international treaties on behalf of the Socialist Republic of Romania; may empower, for this purpose, the Prime Minister or members of the Council of Ministers or diplomatic representatives;
14. In the interest of the defence of the Socialist Republic of Romania, of ensuring public order or state security, proclaims, in case of emergency, in some localities or throughout the territory of the country, the state of necessity.
In the performance of his/her duties, the President of the Socialist Republic of Romania issues presidential decrees and decisions.

1986:77.contentEn:
The Council of Ministers is the supreme body of state administration.
The Council of Ministers exercises general leadership of executive activity throughout the entire territory of the country, having the following main attributions:
1. Establishes general measures for the implementation of internal and external policy;
2. Decides on the necessary measures regarding the organization and ensuring the execution of laws;
3. Leads, coordinates, and controls the activity of ministries and other central bodies of state administration;
4. Elaborates the draft of the single national plan for economic and social development and the draft state budget, as well as any other draft laws; elaborates draft decrees;
5. Establishes measures for the implementation of the single national plan for economic and social development and the state budget; prepares the general report regarding the fulfillment of the single national plan for economic and social development and the general account of the budget year closure;
6. Establishes economic organizations, enterprises, and state institutions of republican interest;
7. Takes measures to ensure public order, defend the interests of the state, and protect the rights of citizens;
8. Takes measures, according to the decisions of the Defence Council, for the general organization of the armed forces and the fixing of annual contingents of citizens who are to be called to fulfill military service;
9. Exercises general leadership in the field of relations with other states and takes measures for the conclusion of international agreements;
10. Supports the activity of mass and public organizations;
11. Exercises, under the conditions provided by law, its leadership and control attributions over the activity of the executive committees and executive bureaus of the people's councils.

1986:87.contentEn:
The people's council shall exercise the following main attributions:
1. Adopts the economic plan and the local budget, approves the account of the closing of the budgetary exercise;
2. Elects and revokes the executive committee or, as the case may be, the executive bureau;
3. Establishes economic organizations, state enterprises and institutions of local interest;
4. Manages, guides and controls the activity of the executive committee or, as the case may be, of the executive bureau, of the local specialized bodies of the state administration, of the economic organizations, enterprises and subordinate institutions;
5. Controls the decisions of hierarchically inferior people's councils;
6. Elects and revokes, according to the law, the judges, the people's assessors and the chief prosecutor of the county or of the municipality of Bucharest.

1986:95.contentEn:
The executive committee of the people's council and the executive bureau of the people's council have the following main attributions:
1. To implement the laws, decrees, as well as the decisions of the Council of Ministers and the other acts of the superior bodies;
2. To execute the resolutions of the people's councils that elected them;
3. To elaborate the drafts of the economic plan and of the local budget;
4. To execute the economic plan and the local budget, to draw up the report regarding the fulfillment of the local economic plan, as well as the closing account of the budgetary exercise;
5. To lead, guide and control the activity of the local specialized bodies of the state administration;
6. To lead, guide, coordinate and control the activity of the economic organizations, of the enterprises and subordinate institutions;
7. To lead, guide and control the activity of the executive committees or, as the case may be, of the executive bureaus of the people's councils hierarchically inferior to the people's councils that elected them.
In the interval between the sessions of the people's council, the executive committee or, as the case may be, the executive bureau also fulfills the attributions thereof, with the exception of those provided at [Art. 87 pct. 1, 2, 4, 5 și 6](#articolul-87), submitting the adopted decisions to the ratification of the people's council at its first session.

1991:27.contentEn:
1. The domicile and residence are inviolable. No one may enter or remain in a person's domicile or residence without their consent.
2. Derogation from the provisions of paragraph (1) is permitted by law in the following situations:
   - a) for the execution of an arrest warrant or a court decision;
   - b) for the removal of a danger concerning a person's life, physical integrity, or property;
   - c) for the defence of national security or public order;
   - d) for the prevention of the spread of an epidemic.
3. Searches may be ordered exclusively by a magistrate and may be carried out only in the forms prescribed by law.
4. Night searches are forbidden, except in cases of flagrant offences.

1991:39.contentEn:
1. Forced labour is prohibited.
2. The following shall not be considered forced labour:
   - a) military service or activities performed in lieu thereof by those who, according to the law, do not perform compulsory military service for religious reasons;
   - b) the work of a convicted person, performed under normal conditions, during detention or conditional release;
   - c) services required in the event of disasters or other dangers, as well as those that are part of normal civil obligations established by law.

1991:62.contentEn:
1. The Chamber of Deputies and the Senate work in separate sittings and in joint sittings. In joint sittings, the proceedings shall be conducted according to regulations adopted by a majority vote of the Deputies and Senators.
2. The Chambers shall meet in a joint sitting for:
   - a) receiving the message of the President of Romania;
   - b) approving the State budget and the State social security budget;
   - c) declaring general or partial mobilization;
   - d) declaring a state of war;
   - e) suspending or ending military hostilities;
   - f) examining the reports of the Supreme Council of National Defence and of the Court of Accounts;
   - g) appointing, upon the proposal of the President of Romania, the Director of the Romanian Intelligence Service and exercising control over the activity of this service;
   - h) fulfilling other powers which, according to the Constitution or the regulations, are exercised in a joint sitting.

1991:72.contentEn:
1. The Parliament shall pass constitutional laws, organic laws, and ordinary laws.
2. Constitutional laws shall be those revising the Constitution.
3. Organic laws shall regulate:
   - a) the electoral system;
   - b) the organisation and functioning of political parties;
   - c) the organisation and holding of referendums;
   - d) the organisation of the Government and of the Supreme Council of National Defence;
   - e) the regime of the state of siege and the state of emergency;
   - f) offences, penalties, and the enforcement of such penalties;
   - g) the granting of amnesty or collective pardon;
   - h) the organisation and functioning of the Superior Council of Magistracy, of the law courts, of the Public Ministry, and of the Court of Accounts;
   - i) the status of public servants;
   - j) administrative litigation;
   - k) the general legal regime of property and inheritance;
   - l) the general regime governing labour relations, trade unions, and social protection;
   - m) the general organisation of education;
   - n) the general regime of religious denominations;
   - o) the organisation of local administration, of the territory, as well as the general regime regarding local autonomy;
   - p) the manner of establishing the exclusive economic zone;
   - r) the other fields for which the Constitution stipulates the enactment of organic laws.

1991:94.contentEn:
The President of Romania shall also have the following powers:
- a) to confer decorations and honorary titles;
- b) to grant the ranks of marshal, general and admiral;
- c) to appoint to public offices, under the conditions provided by law;
- d) to grant individual pardon.

1991:134.contentEn:
1. The economy of Romania is a market economy.
2. The State must ensure:
   - a) freedom of commerce, protection of fair competition, creation of a favorable framework for the utilization of all factors of production;
   - b) protection of national interests in economic, financial and currency activity;
   - c) stimulation of national scientific research;
   - d) exploitation of natural resources, in accordance with the national interest;
   - e) restoration and protection of the environment, as well as maintaining ecological balance;
   - f) creation of the necessary conditions for increasing the quality of life.

1991:144.contentEn:
The Constitutional Court has the following powers:
- a) to rule on the constitutionality of laws prior to their promulgation, upon notification by the President of Romania, by one of the Speakers of the two Chambers, by the Government, by the High Court of Cassation and Justice, by a number of at least 50 Deputies or at least 25 Senators, as well as ex officio, on the initiatives for the revision of the Constitution;
- b) to rule on the constitutionality of the Parliament's regulations, upon notification by one of the Speakers of the two Chambers, by a parliamentary group or by a number of at least 50 Deputies or at least 25 Senators;
- c) to rule on the exceptions raised before the courts of law regarding the unconstitutionality of laws and ordinances;
- d) to ensure the observance of the procedure for the election of the President of Romania and to confirm the results of the suffrage;
- e) to ascertain the existence of circumstances justifying the interim in the exercise of the office of President of Romania and to communicate the ascertained facts to the Parliament and the Government;
- f) to give a consultative opinion for the proposal to suspend the President of Romania from office;
- g) to ensure the observance of the procedure for the organization and conduct of the referendum and to confirm its results;
- h) to verify the fulfillment of the conditions for the exercise of the legislative initiative by citizens;
- i) to rule on disputes having as object the constitutionality of a political party.

2003:27.contentEn:
1. The domicile and the residence are inviolable. No one may enter or remain in the domicile or residence of a person without his consent.
2. Derogation from the provisions of paragraph (1) shall be permissible by law in the following situations:
   - a) execution of an arrest warrant or of a court sentence;
   - b) removal of any danger to a person's life, physical integrity, or property;
   - c) defence of national security or public order;
   - d) prevention of the spread of an epidemic.
3. Search shall be ordered by a judge and carried out under the conditions and in the forms provided by law.
4. Searches during the night shall be forbidden, save for flagrant offences.

2003:42.contentEn:
1. Forced labour is prohibited.
2. The following shall not constitute forced labour:
   - a) activities for the fulfillment of military duties, as well as those carried out, according to the law, in their place, for religious or conscientious reasons;
   - b) the work of a convicted person, performed under normal conditions, during the period of detention or conditional release;
   - c) services required in the event of calamities or other danger, as well as those that are part of the normal civil obligations established by law.

2003:65.contentEn:
1. The Chamber of Deputies and the Senate shall work in separate sittings.
2. The Chambers shall also carry out their proceedings in joint sittings, according to a regulation adopted by the majority vote of the deputies and senators, for:
   - a) receiving the message of the President of Romania;
   - b) approving the state budget and the state social security budget;
   - c) declaring total or partial mobilization;
   - d) declaring the state of war;
   - e) suspending or ceasing military hostilities;
   - f) approving the national defence strategy of the country;
   - g) examining the reports of the Supreme Council of National Defence;
   - h) appointing, upon the proposal of the President of Romania, the directors of the intelligence services and exercising control over the activity of these services;
   - i) appointing the People's Advocate;
   - j) establishing the status of deputies and senators, establishing their allowance and other rights thereof;
   - k) fulfilling other attributions which, according to the Constitution or the regulation, are exercised in joint sitting.

2003:73.contentEn:
1. Parliament shall pass constitutional laws, organic laws, and ordinary laws.
2. Constitutional laws are those revising the Constitution.
3. Organic laws shall regulate:
   - a) the electoral system; the organisation and operation of the Permanent Electoral Authority;
   - b) the organisation, operation, and financing of political parties;
   - c) the status of deputies and senators, the establishment of their allowance and other rights thereof;
   - d) the organisation and conduct of referendums;
   - e) the organisation of the Government and of the Supreme Council of National Defence;
   - f) the regime of the state of partial or total mobilisation of the armed forces and the state of war;
   - g) the regime of the state of siege and the state of emergency;
   - h) offences, penalties, and the regime for the execution thereof;
   - i) the granting of amnesty or collective pardon;
   - j) the status of civil servants;
   - k) administrative litigation;
   - l) the organisation and operation of the Superior Council of Magistracy, of the courts of law, of the Public Ministry, and of the Court of Accounts;
   - m) the general legal regime of property and inheritance;
   - n) the general organisation of education;
   - o) the organisation of local public administration, of the territory, as well as the general regime regarding local autonomy;
   - p) the general regime regarding labour relations, trade unions, employers' organisations, and social protection;
   - r) the status of national minorities in Romania;
   - s) the general regime of religious denominations;
   - t) other fields for which the Constitution provides for the adoption of organic laws.

2003:94.contentEn:
The President of Romania also performs the following duties:
- a) confers decorations and honorary titles;
- b) grants the ranks of marshal, general, and admiral;
- c) appoints to public offices, under the conditions provided by law;
- d) grants individual pardon.

2003:135.contentEn:
1. The economy of Romania is a market economy, based on free initiative and competition.
2. The State must ensure:
   - a) the freedom of commerce, the protection of fair competition, the creation of a favorable framework for harnessing all factors of production;
   - b) the protection of national interests in economic, financial and currency activity;
   - c) the stimulation of national scientific and technological research, of art, and the protection of copyright;
   - d) the exploitation of natural resources, in accordance with the national interest;
   - e) the reconstruction and protection of the environment, as well as the maintenance of ecological balance;
   - f) the creation of the necessary conditions for raising the quality of life;
   - g) the application of regional development policies in accordance with the objectives of the European Union.

2003:146.contentEn:
The Constitutional Court has the following powers:
- a) to rule on the constitutionality of laws, prior to their promulgation, upon notification by the President of Romania, by one of the Speakers of the two Chambers, by the Government, by the High Court of Cassation and Justice, by the People's Advocate, by a number of at least 50 deputies or at least 25 senators, as well as ex officio, on the initiatives for the revision of the Constitution;
- b) to rule on the constitutionality of treaties or other international agreements, upon notification by one of the Speakers of the two Chambers, by a number of at least 50 deputies or at least 25 senators;
- c) to rule on the constitutionality of the Parliament's regulations, upon notification by one of the Speakers of the two Chambers, by a parliamentary group or by a number of at least 50 deputies or at least 25 senators;
- d) to rule on objections of unconstitutionality regarding laws and ordinances, raised before the courts of law or commercial arbitration; the objection of unconstitutionality may also be raised directly by the People's Advocate;
- e) to settle legal disputes of a constitutional nature between public authorities, at the request of the President of Romania, of one of the Speakers of the two Chambers, of the Prime Minister or of the President of the Superior Council of Magistracy;
- f) to ensure the observance of the procedure for the election of the President of Romania and to confirm the results of the suffrage;
- g) to ascertain the existence of circumstances justifying the interim in the exercise of the office of President of Romania and to communicate the findings to the Parliament and the Government;
- h) to give advisory opinion for the proposal to suspend the President of Romania from office;
- i) to ensure the observance of the procedure for the organisation and conduct of the referendum and to confirm its results;
- j) to verify the fulfilment of the conditions for the exercise of the legislative initiative by citizens;
- k) to rule on appeals having as object the constitutionality of a political party;
- l) to perform other duties provided by the organic law of the Court.
